{"cursor":"11462","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nIn propositional logic, 'transposition' Moore and\nParker is a valid rule of replacement that permits one to switch the\nantecedent with the consequent of a conditional statement in a logical proof if\nthey are also both negated. It is the inference from the truth of \"A implies B\"\nthe truth of \"Not-B implies not-A\", and conversely. Brody, Bobuch A.\n\"Glossary of Logical Terms\". Encyclopedia of Philosophy. Vol. 5â6, p. 76.\nMacmillan, 1973. Copi, Irving M. Symbolic Logic. 5th ed. Macmillan,\n1979. See the Rules of Replacement, pp. 39-40. It is very closely related\nto the rule of inference modus tollens. It is the rule that:\n\n:(P Q) \\Leftrightarrow ( Q P)\n\nWhere \" \\Leftrightarrow \" is a metalogical symbol representing \"can\nbe replaced in a proof with.\"\n","linknr":210,"url":"Transposition_(logic)","recorded":1362903498,"links":11,"instances":["formal","mathematics","traditional_logic","rule_of_inference","logic","logic","logic"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Rules of inference","Theorems in propositional logic"],"headings":["Formal notation","Traditional logic","Transposition in mathematical logic","Proof","See also","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/1/4/014cced2b73c22eb88cdc6901afb0c9d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/1/4/014cced2b73c22eb88cdc6901afb0c9d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/3/7/e372e998f5121e0b8ec3fa9aca6f3d76.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/f/7/bf73c9341a48c47c84a48dad635ff940.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/7/a/77a4b7be1af4559a587fc6a6eb90aeea.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/4/8/f482419caa75eb4d59fc7c74fa0816bc.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/6/8/46869208828ab5c0a545a0d1eb07468f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/8/e/48e16a4e3a881e6ad393cf2d69cd6a78.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/0/c/80caac1585376e6983c297aee8d009a9.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/a/f/8aff8e4886b1492bcd660fde012